  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Culture of Dialogue/ Sa&apos; Gar Winne</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">-	To facilitate intra and inter- communal dialogue, ensuring grassroots participation and including women, youth, minorities, and civil society. 
-	To provide opportunities for Muslim and Rakhine to engage informally through joint activities 
-	To foster tolerance through cultural mediums, civic education and awareness raising activities to dispel misinformation about religion.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">&#x2022;	Dialogue awareness sessions will be carried out in targeted villages to select the participants of the trainings.
&#x2022;	Selected participants will receive three modules of three-day trainings in Community dialogue facilitation, Peace and conflict analysis, and Personal leadership.
&#x2022;	Dialogue facilitators will constitute two dialogue forums per village which occur once a month, where they carry out community dialogue exercises, discuss the conflicts which affect them, and work towards peaceful coexistence. 
&#x2022;	The dialogue group agree on and carry out specific actions (e.g. cooking classes, sports), putting the interactions and trust built during community dialogues to practice. 
&#x2022;	Community facilitators will act as a bridge between different communities to support them to engage informally in joint actions. 
&#x2022;	The selection of participants prioritises the inclusion of women, youth, people with disabilities, and other groups who are usually marginalised in community dialogues.
&#x2022;	Over the course of the project, once women groups are sufficiently empowered to express their voices during dialogues, the groups are mixed.</narrative>
  </description>
